      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        How to Read a Queensland Certificate of Title: A Seller's Guide
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The title document is the legal record of your ownership. Before you list your Brisbane property, it is worth knowing how to read it and what to check.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most people receive their title document at settlement and file it away without reading it closely. That is understandable. At the time of purchase, you have a solicitor checking the title for issues and a bank reviewing it as security. The document itself can appear dense if you are not familiar with the structure. But when you come to sell, having a basic understanding of what your title says, and what to check before you list, can save time and avoid surprises that slow down the sale process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a Queensland certificate of title is</h2>
      <p>Queensland operates under the Torrens title system, which means legal ownership of land is established by registration on a government-maintained register, not through chains of paper deeds. The Titles Registry, maintained by Titles Queensland, is the authoritative record. Your certificate of title is essentially a printed extract from that register confirming that you are the registered owner of a specific parcel of land and describing any registered interests that attach to it.</p>

      <p>Importantly, the document you received when you purchased may be out of date. Any registrations that have occurred since your purchase, your mortgage, any subsequent dealings, will not appear on the original document. The current state of your title is what is on the register at Titles Queensland today, not what was printed at your settlement. This is why your solicitor always orders a current title search when preparing contracts for sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The lot and plan number</h2>
      <p>Every Queensland property has a lot and plan number that uniquely identifies it in the Titles Registry. The format is typically "Lot [number] on [plan type][plan number]", for example "Lot 12 on RP 123456" or "Lot 5 on SP 200000". The plan type indicates the survey plan type: RP (registered plan) for older surveys, SP (survey plan) for more modern subdivisions, and BUP or GTP for building unit plans and group title plans used in unit and townhouse developments.</p>

      <p>This lot and plan number is the reference used in all legal documents relating to the property, including the contract for sale, the mortgage, and all title search results. It should match the description in any contract your solicitor prepares. If there is ever a discrepancy between what the agent has on file and what the title says, the title description controls.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The registered owner and how ownership is held</h2>
      <p>This section confirms who is legally recorded as owning the property. For individual owners, it shows the full legal name or names. For companies, it shows the company name and ACN. For trusts, it typically shows the trustee's name with a reference to the trust.</p>

      <p>Where a property is owned by more than one person, the title will show whether the co-owners hold as joint tenants or as tenants in common. Joint tenancy means the owners hold equal undivided shares and the right of survivorship applies: if one owner dies, their interest passes automatically to the surviving owner. Tenants in common means each owner holds a defined share that can be dealt with separately: they can sell, mortgage, or bequeath their share independently. If your title shows tenants in common, it will also show the percentage share held by each owner.</p>

      <p>Before listing, confirm that the names on your title match the names in which any contract will be signed. A discrepancy between the legal names on title and the names on the contract creates a problem that your solicitor will need to resolve before settlement can occur. This is a surprisingly common issue, particularly where a name has changed after purchase (through marriage, for example) and the title was never updated.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Encumbrances, caveats, and notifications</h2>
      <p>This section is the most important part of the title for a seller to understand. It lists all registered interests that other parties hold over your property. Common items include the following.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Mortgages.</strong> Your lender's security interest over the property. This is expected and normal. It will be discharged at settlement from the sale proceeds. Your solicitor coordinates this discharge with your lender, and it is a standard part of every residential sale in Queensland. You do not need to do anything special to prepare for this, other than contacting your lender to confirm the discharge process and any break costs if you have a fixed rate loan.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Easements.</strong> An easement is a registered right that allows another party to use part of your land for a specific purpose. The most common in Brisbane residential properties are drainage easements (allowing the council or an adjoining owner to maintain a drainage infrastructure that crosses your land), electricity and telecommunications easements (allowing the relevant utility to access infrastructure on your property), and access easements (allowing a neighbouring property to access your land for a specific purpose). Easements run with the land: they are not extinguished when you sell, and a buyer acquires the property subject to them. Your solicitor will disclose them in the contract. What matters is that you are aware of any easements before listing, so that they can be accurately reflected in the contract terms and are not a surprise to a buyer who discovers them during due diligence.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Caveats.</strong> A caveat is a notice lodged by a third party claiming an interest in the property. Unlike a mortgage or easement, a caveat is not a formal registered right; it is a warning to the world that someone asserts they have an interest. A caveat prevents dealings with the title (including a sale) until it is resolved. Common sources of caveats include a former co-owner who claims an interest was not properly extinguished, a builder or contractor who claims they are owed money and asserts a construction lien, a party who claims they have a contract to purchase the property that was not completed, and family law disputes where one party claims an interest in a property owned in another party's name alone.</p>

      <p>If your title search shows an unexpected caveat, this is a matter for your solicitor immediately. A caveat that is lodged without proper basis can be removed through the Titles Registry process or through the courts, but it takes time. Discovering a caveat after a contract is signed creates significant pressure on everyone involved. The better outcome is to identify and resolve it before the property goes to market.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Notifications.</strong> Queensland titles may also show notifications, which are recorded matters that do not restrict dealings but must be disclosed. Environmental notifications, heritage listings, and statutory charges for unpaid rates are examples. Your solicitor will advise on which notifications are relevant to your sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to get your current title before listing</h2>
      <p>Your solicitor will order a current title search as part of preparing the contract for sale, so you will see the current state of the title at that point regardless. But if you want to check it earlier, for example when you are deciding whether to proceed with a sale or engaging an agent to give you a market appraisal, you can order a title search directly through Titles Queensland online. The cost is modest and the search is returned quickly.</p>

      <p>When reviewing the title yourself, the things to check are: that the registered owner matches the name in which you intend to sign the contract; that you are aware of all encumbrances shown and understand which ones will be discharged at settlement (your mortgage) versus which will pass to the buyer (easements); and that there are no caveats or unexpected notifications that would need to be resolved before sale.</p>

      <p>Most sellers find their title is straightforward. Mortgage registered, no caveats, perhaps a drainage easement along the rear boundary that has been there since the subdivision. If that is what yours shows, hand it to your solicitor as part of the normal conveyancing process and move on. But the ones who discover a problem early are always better positioned than the ones who discover it under contract pressure.</p>

